# Darwin ML Platform - Cursor Agent Rules

## Initial Context

At the start of every new conversation, you MUST read the `START_CHAT.md` file to understand:
- The Darwin platform architecture and components
- Setup workflow (init.sh → setup.sh → start.sh)
- Key files and their purposes
- Service dependencies
- Common operations and troubleshooting steps

## Project Context

This is the Darwin ML Platform - an enterprise-grade, end-to-end machine learning platform. This repository handles deployment orchestration - building Docker images and deploying the entire platform to Kubernetes using Helm charts.

## Key Files Reference

- `START_CHAT.md` - Agent entry point with platform overview (READ THIS FIRST)
- `services.yaml` - Application registry defining available services, datastores, operators
- `service-dependencies.yaml` - Service-to-service and service-to-datastore dependencies
- `.setup/enabled-services.yaml` - User-selected services config (generated by init.sh)
- `.setup/config.env` - Runtime configuration with KUBECONFIG and DOCKER_REGISTRY
- `helm/darwin/` - Main Helm umbrella chart
- `docs/AWS_DEPLOYMENT_REFINEMENT.md` - AWS cloud deployment guide

## Conventions

- Each submodule follows `.odin/` conventions with build.sh, setup.sh, start.sh
- Services are organized by feature: Compute, Workspace, Feature Store, MLflow, Serve, Catalog, Chronos, Workflow
- Local development uses Kind cluster with local registry at localhost:5000

## Common Tasks

When asked to:
- **Debug a service**: Check `kubectl logs/describe`, review service-dependencies.yaml
- **Add a new service**: Edit services.yaml, add Helm chart, update init.sh/start.sh
- **Enable/disable services**: Edit .setup/enabled-services.yaml
- **Deploy to cloud**: Refer to docs/AWS_DEPLOYMENT_REFINEMENT.md
